          "Comments",
          "Limitations"
        ],
        [
          "Classification",
          "K-12 / Large-Scale Digital Assessment",
          "Not Applicable",
          "Assessment behavior / Time-management performance",
          "Efficient (positive class) vs Not efficient in block B",
          "2464 8th-grade students; 1232 labeled training instances and 1232 holdout instances",
          "NAEP Mathematics assessment (two-block assessment)",
          "Assessment interaction logs from block A",
          "AutoML and expert-engineered log features. TSFRESH: time-series features from seconds per action, seconds per problem, seconds per item, and seconds per action in the last 5 minutes. Featuretools: hierarchical/relational features aggregated at student level from row-, item-, and student-level tables. Expert features: time per item, number of actions, answer-popularity features, first/last-5-minute features.",
          "Prediction made after block A to predict behavior in block B; separate models for first 10 minutes, first 20 minutes, and full 30 minutes of block A",
          "Organizers provided only block A logs, while labels were derived from block B. Data were split into train/holdout. Authors created matched 10-, 20-, and 30-minute versions of the training data. TSFRESH default feature extraction yielded 467/516/460 features; Featuretools yielded 2980 per time length; expert features yielded 644/647/990. Authors proposed a multi-phase feature selection procedure: one-feature CART models with 4-fold CV and AUC filtering, removal of features predictive of train-vs-holdout membership, then correlation-based redundancy removal. Final selected feature sets had 413, 517, and 530 features.",
          "Extra-Trees, Random Forest, XGBoost ",
          "Competition holdout evaluation; internal 4-fold cross-validation on training data; Bayesian hyperparameter optimization; final submission scored on held-out NAEP competition leaderboard",
          "{Final leaderboard: Cohen’s kappa = 0.2116, AUC = 0.6653, Aggregate score = 0.5422; Public leaderboard: Cohen’s kappa = 0.2799, AUC = 0.6676, Aggregate score = 0.6351}",
          "This is a student-modeling / behavioral prediction paper rather than a classic academic-performance paper. The outcome is explicitly time management skill, not assessment score. The paper’s main contribution is methodological: comparing AutoML feature engineering approaches. TSFRESH features outperformed Featuretools and expert-engineered features on average, but were also the hardest to interpret.",
          "Outcome is not a conventional academic success variable. Potential overfitting/generalizability concerns are suggested by the gap between public and final leaderboard results. AutoML features may be dataset- and software-specific. Interpretability analysis is exploratory and based on only six experts."
        ]
      ],
      "index": 8
    }
  ],
